SECOND REGULAR SESSION
HOUSE COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE FOR
HOUSE BILL NO. 2587
103RD GENERAL ASSEMBLY
6127H.02C JOSEPH ENGLER, Chief Clerk
AN ACT
To repeal section 577.800, RSMo, and to enact in lieu thereof three new sections relating to
unmanned aircraft, with penalty provisions and an emergency clause.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the state of Missouri, as follows:
Section A. Section 577.800, RSMo, is repealed and three new sections enacted in lieu
2 thereof, to be known as sections 577.800, 589.900, and 589.902, to read as follows:
577.800. 1. A person commits the offense of unlawful use of unmanned aircraft over
2 an open-air facility or critical infrastructure facility if he or she purposely:
3 (1) Operates an unmanned aircraft within a vertical distance of four hundred feet from
4 the ground and within the property line of an open-air facility; [or]
5 (2) Uses an unmanned aircraft with the purpose of delivering to a person within an
6 open-air facility any object described in subdivision (1) or (2) of subsection 4 of this section;
7 (3) Uses an unmanned aircraft within the boundary of any critical infrastructure
8 facility; or
9 (4) Operates an unmanned aircraft within a vertical distance of four hundred
10 feet from the ground and within the property line of a critical infrastructure facility in
11 furtherance of any violation of criminal law.
12 2. For purposes of this section, "open-air facility" shall mean any sports, theater,
13 music, performing arts, or other entertainment facility with a capacity of five [thousand]
14 hundred people or more and not completely enclosed by a roof or other structure. For
15 purposes of this section, "critical infrastructure facility" shall have the same meaning as
16 section 569.086.
17 3. The provisions of this section shall not prohibit the operation of an unmanned
18 aircraft by:
EXPLANATION — Matter enclosed in bold-faced brackets [thus] in the above bill is not enacted and is
intended to be omitted from the law. Matter in bold-face type in the above bill is proposed language.

HCS HB 2587 2
19 (1) An employee of an open-air facility or critical infrastructure facility at the
20 direction of the president or chief executive officer of the open-air facility or critical
21 infrastructure facility;
22 (2) A person who has written consent from the president or chief executive officer of
23 the open-air facility or critical infrastructure facility;
24 (3) An employee of a law enforcement agency, fire department, or emergency
25 medical service in the exercise of official duties;
26 (4) A government official or employee in the exercise of official duties;
27 (5) A public utility or a rural electric cooperative if:
28 (a) The unmanned aircraft is used for the purpose of inspecting, repairing, or
29 maintaining utility transmission or distribution lines or other utility equipment or
30 infrastructure;
31 (b) The utility or cooperative notifies the open-air facility or critical infrastructure
32 facility before flying the unmanned aircraft, except during an emergency; and
33 (c) The person operating the unmanned aircraft does not physically enter the
34 prohibited space without an escort provided by the open-air facility or critical infrastructure
35 facility; or
36 (6) An employee of a railroad in the exercise of official duties on any land owned or
37 operated by a railroad corporation regulated by the Federal Railroad Administration.
38 4. The offense of unlawful use of unmanned aircraft over an open-air facility or
39 critical infrastructure facility shall be punishable as an infraction unless the person uses an
40 unmanned aircraft for:
41 (1) Delivering a gun, knife, weapon, or other article, including any explosive device
42 or material, that may be used in such manner to endanger the life of an employee or guest at
43 an open-air facility or critical infrastructure facility, in which case the offense is a class B
44 felony; or
45 (2) Delivering a controlled substance, as that term is defined under section 195.010,
46 in which case the offense is a class D felony.
47 5. Each open-air facility or critical infrastructure facility shall post a sign warning
48 of the provisions of this section. The sign shall be at least eleven inches by fourteen inches
49 and posted in a conspicuous place.
589.900. 1. For the purposes of sections 589.900 to 589.902, the following terms
2 mean:
3 (1) "Authorized individuals", peace officers, as defined in section 590.010, who
4 are certified in accordance with federal requirements, including the Homeland Security
5 Act of 2002, Public Law 107-296, as amended, when applicable, to conduct unmanned
6 aircraft and unmanned aerial system mitigation;

HCS HB 2587 3
7 (2) "Mitigate", any of the following actions:
8 (a) During the operation of an unmanned aircraft system, to detect, identify,
9 monitor, or track the unmanned aircraft system or unmanned aircraft, without prior
10 consent, including by means of intercept or other access of a wire communication, an
11 oral communication, or an electronic communication used to control the unmanned
12 aircraft system or unmanned aircraft;
13 (b) To warn the operator of the unmanned aircraft system or unmanned aircraft,
14 including by passive or active and direct or indirect physical, electronic, radio, or
15 electromagnetic means, or through the use of remote identification broadcast or other
16 means;
17 (c) To disrupt control of the unmanned aircraft system or unmanned aircraft,
18 without prior consent, including by disabling the unmanned aircraft system or
19 unmanned aircraft by intercepting, interfering, or causing interference with wire, oral,
20 electronic, or radio communications used to control the unmanned aircraft system or
21 unmanned aircraft;
22 (d) To seize or exercise control of the unmanned aircraft system or unmanned
23 aircraft; or
24 (e) To use reasonable force, if necessary, to disable, damage, or destroy the
25 unmanned aircraft system or unmanned aircraft.
26 2. The terms "unmanned aircraft" and "unmanned aircraft system" shall have
27 the meanings given such terms in 49 U.S.C. Section 44801.
589.902. 1. To the greatest extent permissible under applicable federal law,
2 including the Homeland Security Act of 2002, Pub. L. 107-296, as amended, authorized
3 individuals in this state shall be empowered to take necessary action to mitigate a
4 credible threat that an unmanned aircraft or unmanned aircraft system poses to the
5 safety or security of people, facilities, assets, a venue or set of venues used for large-scale
6 public gatherings or events, critical infrastructure, or correctional facilities.
7 2. Nothing in this section shall be construed to limit the power of a law
8 enforcement officer in this state to seize an unmanned aircraft system or unmanned
9 aircraft in the course of their duties. A law enforcement officer may use all lawful
10 means to effect such a seizure, which may include the use of mitigation techniques where
11 permissible.
12 3. Any unmanned aircraft system or unmanned aircraft seized under this section
13 or in connection with a criminal act shall be subject to forfeiture under section 513.607.
Section B. Because immediate action is necessary to address the urgent need of
2 Missouri law enforcement agencies to be able to ensure and provide for the safety and
3 security of Missouri residents from the threat that weaponized unmanned aircraft systems

HCS HB 2587 4
4 present to Missouri, the enactment of sections 589.900 and 589.901 and the repeal and
5 reenactment of section 577.800 of section A of this act are deemed necessary for the
6 immediate preservation of the public health, welfare, peace, and safety, and is hereby declared
7 to be an emergency act within the meaning of the constitution, and the enactment of sections
8 589.900 and 589.901 and the repeal and reenactment of section 577.800 of this act shall be in
9 full force and effect upon its passage and approval.
